article.headline: DeForge adds career-high 24 in victory
article.linkText: Taurasi sets rookie scoring mark in Mercury win
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Diana Taurasi is not only good, she's humble.

Taurasi, the No. 1 pick in last month's draft, became the first
WNBA rookie to start her career with three 20-point games, helping
the Phoenix Mercury to an 84-76 upset of the Seattle Storm on
Friday night.

Then she said she owed Anna DeForge dinner and paid tribute to
her other teammates.

"A lot of people want to say it's just the person scoring, but
I think it's more than that," Taurasi said. "It's the people
around getting you open, getting you the ball. Any time you see one
person having a big night, it's a lot of people putting a lot of
effort into it."

Taurasi, the league's leading scorer with a 23.3-point average,
finished with 22.

DeForge was strong at the end of the game, scoring seven of her
24 points in the final 1:13. Penny Taylor had 13 points and eight
rebounds and the Mercury (2-1) won consecutive games for the first
time since Aug. 7-11, 2002.

"It's nice to have more power offensively for sure," said
DeForge, who averaged about half Taurasi's pace to lead the Mercury
in scoring last year, when they were 8-26 for the WNBA's worst
record.

Sue Bird led Seattle with 22 points, and reigning league MVP
Lauren Jackson had 20 and 11 rebounds, scoring in double figures
for the 56th straight game.

Betty Lennox added 13 points and Sheri Sam 10 for the Storm, who
weren't able to improve on their franchise-first 2-0 start.

"We talked about coming into this game that we need to win some
games on the road," Bird said. "It leaves a sour taste in your
mouth."

Bird and Taurasi, who helped the University of Connecticut win
the 2002 NCAA championship and will be reunited as teammates this
summer on the U.S. Olympic team, played each other to a virtual
standstill.

But the Storm had no counter for DeForge, who matched her career
high -- and helped preserve the win -- with five free throws and a
layup down the stretch.

Her fast-break basket with 54.6 seconds left sent Phoenix to a
78-71 lead after Tamara Moore outleaped Lennox on a jump ball.

"From start to finish, they had a lot more energy than we
did," Seattle coach Anne Donovan said.

Taurasi had 13 points and all five assists in the first half,
including four points and an assist during a 12-3 run that lifted
the Mercury to a 36-30 lead with 3:30 left.

Jackson got the Storm within 37-34 with two free throws with 37
seconds left, but Taurasi stretched the lead to 39-35 with a
turnaround in the final seconds.

Taylor had five points in the first 2:29 of the second half
during a 12-4 surge that lifted the Mercury to a 51-39 lead.

With 13:03 to go, DeForge made a 3-pointer for another 12-point
lead, but then Bird had a 3-pointer and Lennox and Jackson scored
four points each. The Storm crept within 67-63 on two free throws
by Sam with 6:24 to play.

DeForge, 3-of-5 on 3-pointers, made two in the next 2:13,
staking Phoenix to a 73-65 lead.

"Our game plan was to make it a fight defensively, and we did
that," coach Carrie Graf said. "Lauren Jackson had 20, but she
had to fight for that 20, and in Jackson terms it was a quiet 20."
